    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-01-10T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-01-10T07:00:00-05:00" n="12"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d12">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.5/1–1051: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The United States Deputy Representative on the North Atlantic
                        Council</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SCM1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Spofford</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <gloss target="#t_niact1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">niact</hi>
                        </gloss>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-01-10T12:00:00+00:00"
                            >January 10, 1951—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3817. For <persName corresp="#p_PGW1">Perkins</persName> from <persName
                        corresp="#p_SCM1">Spofford</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_BLD1"
                        >Batt</persName>. Re diplomatic status and rank coordination <gloss
                        target="#t_DPB1">DPB</gloss>, and <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss>
                    3681, December 31.<note n="1" xml:id="d12fn1">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>1. Recommend, of course, that Coordinator<note n="2" xml:id="d12fn2">See
                        paragraph 2 of Part B, Section (2) Defense Production, <ref target="#pg_3"
                            >p. 3</ref>.</note> be given US diplomatic status (passport, et cetera)
                    and high personal US rank. While his position is international, he is,
                    nevertheless, “contributed” by US Government.</p>
                <pb facs="0063" n="25" xml:id="pg_25"/>
                <p>2. As to his status in UK, we have discussed with UK deputy who assures us he
                    will be given same diplomatic status as council deputies.</p>
                <p>3. As to his status in other <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NAT</gloss> countries, he
                    will be holding a position unique, except for that of General <persName
                        corresp="#p_E1">Eisenhower</persName>, established by action of all 12
                        <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NAT</gloss> governments, who have recognized the
                    vital importance to North Atlantic defense of finding a dynamic leader for the
                        <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NAT</gloss> defense production effort.
                    Consequently, there is no doubt that he will be received in other countries as a
                    person of highest rank and importance. There should be no bar, from this
                    standpoint, to his talking to any and all government ministers as the occasion
                    demands. We would expect to formalize the <gloss target="#t_NATO1"
                    >NAT</gloss>-wide status of the coordinator as an important element in the
                    formal development of international staff of <gloss target="#t_NATO1"
                        >NATO</gloss>, but hope you will assure <persName corresp="#p_HWR1"
                        >Herod</persName> that we anticipate not the slightest formal difficulties
                    or lack of recognition of the importance of the job of any <gloss
                        target="#t_NATO1">NAT</gloss> governments. [<persName corresp="#p_BLD1"
                        >Batt</persName>.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>[<persName corresp="#p_SCM1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Spofford</hi>
                        </persName>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
